tions</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>EP/J01298X/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>Increasing the size and complexity of atomistic systems in molecular simulations
is the driving force behind development of multi-scale techniques which
describe different regions of the system at different levels of
theory, e.g. using quantum mechanics (QM) where high accuracy is necessary and 
Molecular Mechanics (MM) where such a lower level of description is adequate, but
taking advantage of the high speed of MM models is essential due to the overall size of the system.

Chemical processes such as reactant transport, diffusion,
membrane transport, ionic conductance, corrosive fracture of materials
or solvated chemical reactions, when modelled using such a QM/MM approach
all require reassignment of the QM and MM regions during the course of the
simulation. There is a unique opportunity to bring together three
participants, each of whom are in possession of an essential
component, to implement and widely disseminate a novel software tool.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:potentialImpactText>The integration of adaptive QM/MM techniques
into the AMBER software will benefit a very large user base: with over
8,000 downloads from unique IP addresses of the AMBER Tools package 
and &amp;gt;500 sites which use the AMBER MD engines it is clear that this
addition will have a wide reach. This project will therefore have an
extremely broad impact.

Researchers who are currently using AMBER to study biological and biochemical 
systems using QM/MM will now be able to automate the selection of the QM region. 
Further researchers who have not been using such techniques due to the lack
of adaptivity will now be able to. 

Beyond academia, these users are primarily in the pharmaceutical and the wider
healthcare industries. These fields rely heavily on atomic scale modelling.</gtr:potentialImpactText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2012-06-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/798CB33D-C79E-4578-83F2-72606407192C"><gtr:id>798CB33D-C79E-4578-83F2-72606407192C</gtr:id><gtr:name>EPSRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2011-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>6800</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>We have developed a piece of software that enables the use of our simulation methodology in the AMBER software package that is widely used to simulate bimolecular models.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>Our simulation method will be available to the user community of AMBER.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>64404C92-F5C7-4735-B376-75F72740F7BA</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>56dd6e93325275.81640099</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Chemicals,Healthcare,Manufacturing, including Industrial Biotechology</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutput><gtr:description>We created a new module in the CP2K software package that enables the multi-resolution QM/MM (quantum mechanical/molecular mechanical) simulations with adaptive QM regions, i.e. the assignment of atoms to the QM region can change during the simulation.</gtr:description><gtr:id>38F84C73-AD21-41C3-B63C-624C039CC447</gtr:id><gtr:impact>The new module enhances the capability of cp2k. We are not aware of any way to track the individual usage of modules.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>58c681f93b3f47.66815248</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:title>adaptive QM/MM module in the CP2K software package</gtr:title><gtr:type>Software</gtr:type><gtr:url>http://www.cp2k.org</gtr:url><gtr:yearFirstProvided>2012</gtr:yearFirstProvided></gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutput><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutput><gtr:description>We implemented a module in the AMBER software package to carry out adaptive QM/MM simulations. These are multi-resolution molecular dynamics simulations in which part of the system is described using Quantum Mechanics, while the other part is described by Molecular Mechanics. Our module enables on-the-fly reassignment of atoms between these regions.</gtr:description><gtr:id>5F0C7C12-3568-48B0-AF75-F0D1318951C5</gtr:id><gtr:impact>The capability of the AMBER package was enhanced. It is not possible to track the individual usage of amber modules.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>58c6839ce7d5c3.17654698</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:title>Module to carry out adaptive QM/MM simulations in the AMBER software package</gtr:title><gtr:type>Software</gtr:type><gtr:url>http://ambermd.org</gtr:url><gtr:yearFirstProvided>2012</gtr:yearFirstProvided></gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutput></gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>08F0D98E-E1BE-4EB5-A66A-BBBA533711D0</gtr:id><gtr:title>The adaptive buffered force QM/MM method in the CP2K and AMBER software packages.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Journal of computational chemistry</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/6f0e6be49d9bb8e89ecfa79a485a4264"><gtr:id>6f0e6be49d9bb8e89ecfa79a485a4264</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Mones L</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2015-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>0192-8651</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>doi_55f974974bccbc5d</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>EF1D7CF5-F1C1-45A1-9B96-34204EA1A402</gtr:id><gtr:title>Tests of an adaptive QM/MM calculati